{
  "decision_summary": "The chip temperature (174.6°C) severely violates the 45°C limit. The most effective immediate action is to maximize the heat spreader's ability to conduct heat laterally and vertically. I will increase the spreader material conductivity to its upper bound (500.0 W/mK) and slightly increase the spreader height to improve the thermal cross-section, while keeping the width change conservative to avoid boundary violations seen in previous runs.",
  "changes": [
    {
      "path": "materials.spreader_material.conductivity",
      "action": "set",
      "old": 500.0,
      "new": 500.0,
      "reason": "Maintain maximum conductivity as it is already at the upper bound; this is the primary lever for lateral spreading."
    },
    {
      "path": "components.2.height",
      "action": "set",
      "old": 0.1,
      "new": 0.12,
      "reason": "Increase spreader height by 20% (within 1.5x limit) to provide more vertical thermal mass and conduction path above the chip without exceeding domain bounds."
    },
    {
      "path": "components.2.width",
      "action": "set",
      "old": 0.7,
      "new": 0.84,
      "reason": "Increase spreader width by 20% to extend lateral heat spreading area towards the cold boundaries, staying well within the [0.2, 1.0] domain limit."
    }
  ],
  "expected_effects": [
    "Significant reduction in chip peak temperature due to improved lateral and vertical heat spreading.",
    "More uniform temperature distribution across the top layer.",
    "Move the design closer to feasibility (<= 45°C)."
  ],
  "risk_notes": [
    "Even with these changes, the temperature gap is large (~130°C), so multiple iterations may be required.",
    "Increasing spreader dimensions reduces the available air/insulation space, though no specific constraint forbids this yet.",
    "Ensure the spreader does not overlap with the chip (y0=0.32 + h=0.12 = 0.44, chip top is 0.32, so they are stacked correctly)."
  ]
}
